with braille it allowed a blind person to read almost anything printed even some handwriting and even appreciate variances in typography such as italics optacons developed a devoted following until the company ceased to produce them in 1996 the technology had become superseded in the marketplace by gadgets that would scan pages but many people continued using their optacons as one such reader wrote what mattered was access and the optacon provided that books newspapers magazines catalogues bills record jackets and the recipes on boxes of cake mix the barriers were down and suddenly everything was within reach for the first time friends lent me their favorite books sent me clippings and dared to share their private thoughts in typewritten letters through engineering a father's love can end up touching thousands of people watch a two part 1972 video about the optacon we are interested in your nostalgic photos and the stories they tell if you d like to share them with the stanford engineering community e mail them to david orenstein manager communications and pr june 2010 right rail 2010 memories february echo from the sun april 1990 the stellar year of the stanford engineering woman astronaut june the optacon history archives stay connected itunes icon google+ icon facebook icon twitter icon linkedin icon stanford university school of engineering 475 via ortega stanford california 94305 4121 650.725 1575 1997 2012 stanford university all rights reserved accreditation info terms of use copyright complaints contact us
